        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Sales Orders Overview",
            Slug = "sales-orders-overview",
            Summary = "What sales orders are, their lifecycle from draft to completion, line items, and how they connect to quotes, jobs, shipments, and invoices.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/sales-orders"]""",
            Tags = """["sales-orders","sales","order-management"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Sales Orders Overview\n\nA Sales Order (SO) is a confirmed commitment to deliver specific parts to a customer at agreed-upon prices. It ties together everything that follows — production, shipping, and invoicing — and traces back to the quote it came from.\n\n### What Is a Sales Order?\n\nA sales order captures:\n- **Who** is ordering (the customer, plus their PO number if they gave you one)\n- **What** they want (line items — each with a part, quantity, and unit price)\n- **When** they need it (requested delivery date)\n- **Payment terms** (such as Net 30 or Net 60)\n- **Tax** (the tax rate applied to the subtotal)\n\nEach order gets a unique order number automatically. That number shows up throughout the app — on shipments, invoices, and the kanban board — so you can always trace back to the original commitment.\n\n### Sales Order Lifecycle\n\nSales orders move through these stages in order:\n\n1. **Draft** — You're still preparing the order. Edit any field, add or remove line items, or delete the order. Draft orders haven't been committed to the customer yet.\n\n2. **Confirmed** — The order has been reviewed and locked in as a commitment. The confirmed date is recorded for you. Production can now begin.\n\n3. **In Production** — Jobs have been created from the order and work is underway on the shop floor.\n\n4. **Partially Shipped** — Some line items have shipped, others haven't. Each line tracks its own shipped-versus-ordered count, so you can see exactly what's outstanding.\n\n5. **Shipped** — Every line item has fully shipped. The order is complete for fulfillment.\n\n6. **Completed** — The order is fully closed — shipped and invoiced. Nothing left to do.\n\n7. **Cancelled** — The order was cancelled before it finished. You can cancel only from Draft or Confirmed. Once production starts, you can't cancel.\n\n### Line Items\n\nEach sales order has one or more line items. A line item includes:\n- **Part** — the part being ordered, picked from the parts catalog\n- **Description** — filled in from the part; you can change it\n- **Quantity** — how many units the customer wants\n- **Unit Price** — price per unit\n- **Line Total** — quantity times unit price, worked out for you\n- **Shipped** — how many have shipped so far\n- **Remaining** — how many are still to ship\n\nOn the order's detail view, shipped counts show in green when fully shipped and yellow when partially shipped.\n\n### How Sales Orders Connect to Other Features\n\n**Quotes:** A sales order can start from an accepted quote. When you convert a quote, the link back to it stays visible on the order — just click it to open the quote.\n\n**Jobs (Kanban):** Order lines drive production. Each line can create one or more jobs on the kanban board. As you move a job through production, the order's fulfillment status keeps up.\n\n**Shipments:** When goods are ready, you create shipments against the order's lines, recording how many units go out. You can ship partially — send 50 of 100 now and the rest later.\n\n**Invoices:** Invoices come from shipments or straight from the order, and stay linked to it for accurate billing.\n\n**Customers:** Every order belongs to a customer. Click the customer name on the order to open their record.\n\n### Financial Summary\n\nEach sales order shows:\n- **Subtotal** — the sum of all line totals\n- **Tax** — the subtotal times the tax rate\n- **Total** — subtotal plus tax\n\nThese update on their own as you add or change line items.\n\n### When to Use Sales Orders\n\n- When a customer accepts a quote and you need to formalize the commitment\n- When a customer sends a purchase order you need to fulfill\n- When you need to track what has shipped versus what's still outstanding\n- When you need to invoice based on what you've fulfilled\n- When you want full traceability from order through production to delivery","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Walkthrough ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
