            Summary = "Tour the eight tabs of the sales order detail panel — Overview, Lines, Schedule, Shipments, Returns, Documents, Invoices, and Activity — and learn what each one shows and the warning badges that flag attention.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 5,
            AppRoutes = """["/sales-orders"]""",
            Tags = """["sales-orders","sales","detail","tabs"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## The Sales Order Detail Workspace\n\nOpening any order from the Sales Orders list gives you a tabbed workspace that holds everything about that order in one place. You can bookmark the open order or copy its link to send a coworker straight to it. The header shows the order number and the customer name — click the name to open the customer. Close the order with the X in the top-right to return to the list.\n\nBelow the header is a bar of **eight tabs**. Some tabs carry a small count so you can see, without clicking, how many lines or shipments or documents an order has. Several tabs also raise a yellow warning triangle when that part of the order needs attention. Here is what each tab does.\n\n### 1. Overview\n\nThe tab you land on. It shows:\n- **Status and header info** — the status, plus Customer PO, the linked Quote (click to open it), Credit Terms, Requested Delivery date, and Confirmed date. Each field appears only when it has a value.\n- **Edit Details (Draft only)** — opens a short form to fill in Customer PO, Credit Terms, and Requested Delivery date. This is where you add those details after converting a quote into an order. See *Editing a Draft Sales Order*.\n- **Fulfillment summary** — three at-a-glance numbers: lines with jobs, lines shipped, and how many shipments have gone out.\n- **Totals** — Subtotal, Tax (with the rate), and the grand Total in bold.\n- **Notes**, a scannable **barcode**, and the dates the order was created and last updated.\n- **Actions** — Confirm (Draft only), Cancel Order (Draft or Confirmed), and Delete (Draft only).\n\n### 2. Lines\n\nThe line-item list: line number, part number (click it when a part is linked), description, quantity, a combined **Shipped / Remaining** count (shipped shows green when fully shipped, yellow when partial), unit price, and line total. On a **Draft** order this tab lets you add, edit, and delete lines. When a line has production jobs, expand the row to see each job's number, stage, who it's assigned to, priority, and due date. The tab shows the line count, and raises a warning triangle when a confirmed line still has no job.\n\n### 3. Schedule\n\nTurns each line into a delivery timeline — order placed, into production, shipped — with each milestone marked Done, Overdue, or Upcoming. A line that's falling behind its target dates is flagged **At Risk**, and the tab raises a warning triangle when any line is at risk. Use it to catch a slipping order before the delivery date arrives.\n\n### 4. Shipments\n\nOne card per shipment, each linking to the shipment and showing carrier, tracking number, shipped and delivered dates, shipping cost, and weight, plus the lines and packages in that shipment. The tab shows how many shipments there are, and raises a warning triangle when the order is only partially shipped (lines still have quantity left to send).\n\n### 5. Returns\n\nOne card per customer return (RMA) tied to this order — return number, status, reason, return date, and links to the job that made the goods and any rework job. A warning triangle appears when a return is still open (not yet closed).\n\n### 6. Documents\n\nAttach, download, and remove files that belong with the order — drawings, the customer's PO, packing instructions, PDFs, photos, Office files, and CAD files, up to 50 MB each. Each file shows its type, size, and when it was uploaded. The tab shows how many files are attached.\n\n### 7. Invoices\n\nEvery invoice raised from this order's shipments. Each card links to the invoice and shows the amount, due date, payment status, and which shipments it covers. A summary compares **Total Invoiced** against the **Order Total** so you can see how much of the order has been billed. A warning triangle appears when a shipment has gone out but hasn't been invoiced yet — your cue to bill the customer.\n\n### 8. Activity\n\nThe running history of the order: confirmations, cancellations, line edits, header changes, and any comments people have left. It's the audit trail for who did what, and when.\n\n### Reading the warning triangles\n\nThe tab warnings are a fast way to triage an order:\n- **Lines** → a confirmed line has no production job yet.\n- **Schedule** → a line is at risk of missing its dates.\n- **Shipments** → the order is only partially shipped.\n- **Returns** → an open return still needs resolving.\n- **Invoices** → a shipment has gone out but hasn't been invoiced.\n\nGlance across the tab bar first: the triangles tell you where the order needs attention before you open a single tab.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Editing a Draft (Article) ────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Editing a Draft Sales Order",
            Slug = "sales-orders-editing-draft",
            Summary = "How to add, edit, and delete line items on a Draft order, edit the header fields (Customer PO, Credit Terms, Requested Delivery), and how a customer's price list auto-fills the line unit price.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 6,
            AppRoutes = """["/sales-orders"]""",
            Tags = """["sales-orders","sales","draft","editing"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Editing a Draft Sales Order\n\nA sales order stays fully editable while it is a **Draft**. Once you Confirm it, the lines and header lock — the order is now a commitment to the customer. This article covers everything you can change on a Draft.\n\n### Editing line items (Lines tab)\n\nOpen the order and go to the **Lines** tab. On a Draft, the tab shows an **Add Line** button, and each row gets Edit and Delete controls.\n\n**Add a line:**\n1. Click **Add Line**. A small form opens below the list.\n2. Search the parts catalog by part number or name and pick the part. (A line can also be a lump-sum or one-off with no catalog part — leave the part blank and just write the description, handy for freight, setup fees, or a special item.)\n3. The **Description** fills in from the part; change it if you need to.\n4. Enter the **Quantity** and **Unit Price**. Quantity can be a partial amount when you sell by weight, length, or time — 2.5 kg, 0.75 hours.\n5. Click **Save**. The line is added and the totals update.\n\n**Edit a line:** Click the pencil on a row to reopen it. You can change the description, quantity, and unit price. The **part itself is fixed** once the line is added — to swap the part, delete the line and add a new one.\n\n**Delete a line:** Click the trash icon and confirm. A Draft order has to keep at least one line, so you can't remove the last one.\n\nEvery add, edit, or delete updates the Subtotal, Tax, and Total right away.\n\n### Customer pricing fills in automatically\n\nWhen you pick a catalog part, the app checks whether that customer has a negotiated price for it on their price list. If they do, the **Unit Price fills in with their agreed price**, so you don't have to look it up. If there's no special price on file, the field stays blank for you to enter. Either way, you can type over the price before saving.\n\n### Editing the header (Overview tab)\n\nThree header fields can be changed on a Draft from the **Overview** tab: **Customer PO**, **Credit Terms**, and **Requested Delivery Date**.\n\n1. On the Overview tab, click **Edit Details**.\n2. A short form opens with the three fields.\n3. Change any of them and click **Save**.\n\nThis matters most right after you convert a quote into an order: a converted order starts with these fields empty, and Overview only shows fields that have a value. **Edit Details** is where you add them — record the customer's PO number, set the payment terms, and lock in the delivery date before you confirm.\n\n### What you can't change, and when\n\n- **Tax rate** is set when you create the order. Header editing covers PO, terms, and delivery only.\n- **Customer** is fixed once the order exists — it decides who gets billed and which price list applies. To bill someone else, start a new order.\n- **After you Confirm**, the Lines tab controls and Edit Details disappear. Lines, header, and totals are locked. If a confirmed order turns out wrong, cancel it (which keeps the record for history) and create a corrected order rather than editing the old one.\n\n### Your work is saved as you go\n\nWhile you're filling in a brand-new order — before you've saved it the first time — your entries are held safely, so an accidental refresh or getting logged out won't wipe them. When you come back, you're offered the chance to pick up where you left off. This is just recovery of the half-finished form; it's separate from the order's Draft status, which is the first stage of an order you've already saved.","sections":[]}"""
