            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 7,
            AppRoutes = """["/sales-orders"]""",
            Tags = """["sales-orders","sales","fulfillment","tracking"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Tracking Fulfillment from a Sales Order\n\nOnce an order is confirmed, the sales order becomes your single window into how that commitment is being fulfilled — from production jobs through shipments to invoicing. You don't have to hunt across the kanban board, shipments, and invoices separately; the SO detail panel rolls it all up.\n\n### The fulfillment summary (Overview tab)\n\nThe Overview tab shows a **Fulfillment** strip with three stats:\n- **Lines with jobs** — e.g. `3/4` means three of the four order lines have at least one production job created. A line without a job isn't yet in production.\n- **Lines shipped** — how many lines are fully shipped.\n- **Shipments** — the total count of shipments raised against the order.\n\nThis is your 5-second health check. `4/4 lines with jobs, 0/4 shipped` tells you the whole order is in production but nothing has gone out yet.\n\n### Per-line job drill-down (Lines tab)\n\nOn the **Lines** tab, any line that has jobs shows an expander chevron. Expand it to see each job linked to that line: **job number** (clickable to open the job), **title**, **stage** (e.g. In Production, QC/Review), **assignee**, **priority**, and **due date**. Archived jobs are flagged. This lets you trace a specific ordered part all the way to the shop-floor work producing it, without leaving the order.\n\n### No-job warnings\n\nA confirmed order line with **no production job** is a fulfillment gap — nobody is making that part yet. You'll see this flagged in two places:\n- The **Lines tab** raises a warning triangle, and the line that's missing a job is highlighted with a \"No job created\" note.\n- These warnings only show once the order is past Draft — a Draft isn't expected to have jobs yet — and they drop off once an order is cancelled.\n\nWhen you see a no-job warning, create the job from the kanban board so the line enters production.\n\n### The Schedule tab\n\nThe **Schedule** tab turns the order's lines into a milestone timeline — order date → production → ship — and flags any line as **At Risk** when its milestones are slipping past their target dates. The tab bar shows a warning triangle when at least one line is at risk. Use this to spot delivery problems early, before the requested delivery date arrives.\n\n### The Invoices rollup (Invoices tab)\n\nThe **Invoices** tab closes the loop on billing. It lists every invoice generated from the order's shipments, each showing amount, due date, payment status, and the shipments it covers. A summary compares **Total Invoiced** to the **Order Total** so you can see how much of the order has been billed.\n\nThe key signal here is the **uninvoiced-shipment warning**: when a shipment has gone out but no invoice covers it yet, the Invoices tab shows a warning triangle and a prompt. That's revenue shipped but not yet billed — your cue to raise the invoice.\n\n### Putting it together\n\nA typical fulfillment read on a confirmed order:\n1. **Overview** → fulfillment stats give the big picture.\n2. **Lines** → any no-job warnings? Drill into each line's jobs for stage/assignee.\n3. **Schedule** → any line at risk of missing its date?\n4. **Shipments** → what has actually gone out?\n5. **Invoices** → any uninvoiced shipments to bill?\n\nThe tab warning triangles let you triage all five of these from the tab bar at a glance.","sections":[]}"""
