            Summary = "What recurring order templates are, how the nightly job auto-generates sales orders from them, the create flow, the interval/next-run model, and why templates are create-and-delete (no edit).",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 8,
            AppRoutes = """["/sales-orders/recurring"]""",
            Tags = """["sales-orders","sales","recurring","automation"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Recurring Order Templates\n\nSome customers order the same parts on a regular cadence — a standing monthly release, a weekly restock. Rather than re-keying the same order every time, you create a **recurring order template** once, and the system generates a fresh sales order from it automatically on schedule.\n\n### Where it lives\n\nOpen recurring templates from the **Recurring** link on the Sales Orders page. The page lists every template with its name, customer, interval, next run date, last generated date, line count, and whether it's Active or Inactive. It's meant for office and management staff, and may not appear on installs that don't run standing orders.\n\n### How auto-generation works\n\nEach night the app checks every active template. When a template's **Next Generation Date** has arrived, it:\n1. Creates a new **Draft sales order** for the template's customer, copying all the template lines (part, description, quantity, unit price).\n2. Stamps the template's **Last Generated** date so you can see it ran.\n3. Moves the template's **Next Generation Date** forward by its **Interval (days)** so it's set up for the next cycle.\n\nThe new order lands as an ordinary Draft in the Sales Orders list and follows the usual path — review, confirm, produce, ship, invoice. A template never ships or confirms anything on its own; it only seeds the Draft, so a person still reviews each release before committing to it.\n\n### Creating a template\n\nClick **New Recurring** to open the dialog and fill in:\n- **Name** — a label for the template (e.g. \"Acme monthly bracket release\"). Required.\n- **Customer** — the customer the generated orders belong to. Required.\n- **Next Run Date** — when the first (or next) order should be generated. Defaults to one week out.\n- **Interval (days)** — how many days between generations (1–365). 30 ≈ monthly, 7 = weekly.\n- **Notes** — optional free-form notes carried for reference.\n- **Lines** — one or more part lines, each with a part, description, quantity, and unit price. At least one line is required; use **Add Line** for more and the trash icon to remove (you must keep at least one).\n\nSave, and the template appears in the list, ready for the nightly job to pick up on its Next Run Date.\n\n### Create-and-delete, not edit\n\nRecurring templates are **create-and-delete only — there is no edit**. The idea is that a standing order stays the same release after release, so changes should be rare. When one does need to change (different quantity, a new part, a price update), **delete the old template and create a new one** with the corrected lines. Deleting a template stops future orders from being generated right away; any orders it already produced are untouched — they carry on as ordinary sales orders.\n\n### When to use a recurring template\n\n- A customer has a blanket / standing order with predictable releases.\n- You want each release to start as a reviewable Draft rather than auto-shipping.\n- The line set is stable enough that occasional delete-and-recreate is acceptable.\n\nIf the order changes every time, a recurring template adds little — just create each order directly instead.","sections":[]}"""
        });

