            AppRoutes = """["/sales-orders"]""",
            Tags = """["sales-orders","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Reading the Schedule Tab, and Acting on It\n\nThe **Schedule** tab is your early-warning system for late deliveries. It lays each order line out as a delivery timeline — order placed, into production, shipped — and marks each milestone Done, Overdue, or Upcoming. A line that's falling behind its target dates is flagged **At Risk**, and the tab raises a warning triangle so you catch it without opening the tab.\n\nWhat to do with it:\n- **Check it on your at-risk orders first thing.** A line goes at risk before the customer's delivery date, not after — that's the point. Seeing it early is what lets you make a call while you still can.\n- **An at-risk flag is telling you the shop-floor work is running late,** not that the order itself is wrong. You clear it by getting the underlying jobs moving — expedite, re-sequence, or reassign — not by touching the order.\n- **Use it to decide whether to warn the customer.** If a line can't recover, a heads-up now beats a missed date later. If it's a day or two, you may just push the jobs.\n\n## Tracing a Return Back to the Job\n\nThe **Returns** tab lists every customer return (RMA) tied to this order, one card each — and, crucially, it links each return to the shop-floor work behind it.\n\n- **Original job** — the job that made the goods that came back. Open it to see who ran it, what stage flagged a problem, and what the inspection notes said. This is where you look when a customer says a part is out of spec.\n- **Rework job** — the job created to fix or replace the return. It appears once rework is under way, so you can track the replacement the same way you tracked the original.\n- Click either link to jump straight to that job. This is the fast path from \"the customer returned five brackets\" to \"here's exactly how they were made and where the fix stands.\"\n- A return stays flagged with a warning triangle until it's closed, so an open RMA doesn't quietly fall off your radar.\n\n## Selling by Weight, Length, or Time\n\nNot every line is whole units. When you sell by the pound, the foot, or the hour, the quantity on a line can be a partial amount — 2.5 kg, 12.75 ft, 0.75 hr — and the line total works out correctly against your unit price.\n\n- **Quantity** must be more than zero; a line for nothing isn't a line.\n- **Unit price** can be zero (a no-charge or sample line) but never negative.\n- The same holds everywhere you enter a line — a new order, editing a Draft, or a recurring template — so a standing order for bulk material behaves the same as a one-off.\n- Whole-unit lines still read as plain whole numbers; you only see decimals when you actually enter them.\n\n## Recovering an Unsaved Order\n\nStarting a new order is often interrupted — a phone call, a browser refresh, a dropped session. Your entries on a not-yet-saved order are held for you, so that interruption doesn't cost you the whole order.\n\n- When you come back to start a new order, you're offered the chance to **pick up where you left off** instead of retyping.\n- This only covers an order you hadn't saved yet. Once you've saved it — even as a Draft — it's a real order in the list and is safe on its own.\n- If you'd rather start clean, decline the offer and the recovered entries are dropped.\n\n## Correcting an Order That's Already Confirmed\n\nYou can freely edit lines, pricing, and header details while an order is a **Draft**. The moment you Confirm it, those become locked — the order is now a promise you've made to the customer.\n\n- **This is a guardrail, not a limitation.** A confirmed order has been communicated and may already be in production; quietly changing its lines or price would leave you and the customer with different versions of the same order.\n- **To fix a confirmed order, cancel it and create a corrected one.** Cancelling keeps the original on record with a Cancelled status, so the history of what happened stays intact — useful if the customer ever asks why there are two orders.\n- **Tax rate and customer are set once, at creation.** The customer decides who gets billed and which price list applies, so to bill someone else you start a fresh order rather than reassigning an existing one.","sections":[]}"""
